/**
 * @file wave.aria
 * @brief 9D Wave Coordinate System for Nikola AGI
 * 
 * ARIA-030: Wave9 Type - Balanced Nonary Wave Mechanics
 * 
 * This module implements the 9-dimensional toroidal coordinate system used by
 * Nikola's UFIE (Unified Field Interference Engine) physics substrate.
 * 
 * The 9 dimensions represent:
 *   - State Space (r, s):     Neuromodulation (dopamine, serotonin, etc.)
 *   - Quantum Space (u, v, w): Superposition states and coherence
 *   - Spatial Space (x, y, z): Physical location in 3D world model
 *   - Time (t):                Temporal coordinate (cyclic buffer)
 * 
 * Each dimension is encoded as a balanced nonary digit (nit), allowing values
 * from -4 to +4. This gives 9^9 = 387,420,489 possible wave states.
 * 
 * The Wave9 type is the uncompressed working format for physics calculations.
 * The nyte type (5 nits) provides compressed encoding for storage/transmission.
 * 
 * Physics Operations:
 *   - wave_interfere: Superposition of two wave states (elementwise addition)
 *   - wave_magnitude: L2 norm in 9D space
 *   - wave_normalize: Scale to unit magnitude
 *   - nyte_from_wave: Compress 9D → 5D encoding
 *   - wave_from_nyte: Decompress 5D → 9D reconstruction
 * 
 * References:
 *   - Nikola Engineering Spec: 9D Toroidal Geometry
 *   - UFIE Physics Kernel: Wave Interference Mechanics
 *   - Balanced Nonary Intrinsics: Arithmetic on nit/nyte types
 */

/**
 * Wave9: 9-Dimensional Wave Coordinate (Uncompressed Format)
 * 
 * This is the primary working representation for wave mechanics in Nikola.
 * Each dimension is a balanced nonary digit (nit: -4 to +4).
 * 
 * Dimensional Semantics:
 *   r, s:    State dimensions (2D state space for neuromodulation)
 *            Resolution: 16x16 grid (coarse-grained modulation)
 *   
 *   t:       Temporal dimension (cyclic time buffer)
 *            Resolution: 128 timesteps (~64ms at 2kHz physics rate)
 *   
 *   u, v, w: Quantum dimensions (3D quantum state space)
 *            Resolution: 32x32x32 grid (superposition states)
 *   
 *   x, y, z: Spatial dimensions (3D physical world model)
 *            Resolution: 64x64x64 grid (high-resolution spatial mapping)
 * 
 * Memory Layout: 9 bytes (1 byte per nit)
 * Addressable States: 9^9 = 387,420,489 unique wave configurations
 */
struct:Wave9 = {
    nit:r;  // State dimension 1: Neuromodulation axis 1
    nit:s;  // State dimension 2: Neuromodulation axis 2
    nit:t;  // Temporal dimension: Time coordinate
    nit:u;  // Quantum dimension 1: Superposition axis 1
    nit:v;  // Quantum dimension 2: Superposition axis 2
    nit:w;  // Quantum dimension 3: Superposition axis 3
    nit:x;  // Spatial dimension 1: Physical X coordinate
    nit:y;  // Spatial dimension 2: Physical Y coordinate
    nit:z;  // Spatial dimension 3: Physical Z coordinate
};

/**
 * Create a zero wave (all dimensions at origin)
 * 
 * @return Wave9 with all coordinates set to 0
 */
pub func:wave_zero = Wave9() {
    pass(Wave9 {
        r: 0, s: 0, t: 0,
        u: 0, v: 0, w: 0,
        x: 0, y: 0, z: 0
    });
};

/**
 * Wave Interference: Superposition of two wave states
 * 
 * In balanced nonary wave mechanics, interference is implemented as
 * elementwise addition of coordinate components. This represents the
 * linear superposition principle from quantum mechanics.
 * 
 * Physics Interpretation:
 *   When two waves interfere, their amplitudes combine additively.
 *   In 9D toroidal space, this manifests as vector addition of
 *   coordinate offsets with modular wraparound at dimension boundaries.
 * 
 * Note: Addition of nit values is saturated to [-4, +4] range.
 * Overflow/underflow represents wave amplitude clipping (physical damping).
 * 
 * @param a First wave state
 * @param b Second wave state
 * @return Interfered wave (superposition of a and b)
 */
pub func:wave_interfere = Wave9(Wave9:a, Wave9:b) {
    pass(Wave9 {
        r: a.r + b.r,
        s: a.s + b.s,
        t: a.t + b.t,
        u: a.u + b.u,
        v: a.v + b.v,
        w: a.w + b.w,
        x: a.x + b.x,
        y: a.y + b.y,
        z: a.z + b.z
    });
};

/**
 * Wave Negation: Invert wave phase
 * 
 * Negation in balanced nonary is trivial - just flip the sign of each
 * component. This represents a 180° phase shift in all dimensions.
 * 
 * Physics Interpretation:
 *   Creates a wave that destructively interferes with the original.
 *   wave_interfere(w, wave_negate(w)) ≈ wave_zero (modulo rounding)
 * 
 * @param w Wave to negate
 * @return Negated wave (phase-inverted)
 */
pub func:wave_negate = Wave9(Wave9:w) {
    pass(Wave9 {
        r: -w.r,
        s: -w.s,
        t: -w.t,
        u: -w.u,
        v: -w.v,
        w: -w.w,
        x: -w.x,
        y: -w.y,
        z: -w.z
    });
};

/**
 * Wave Scaling: Multiply wave amplitude
 * 
 * Scale all components by a constant factor. Used for wave attenuation/
 * amplification in physics simulation.
 * 
 * Note: Result is saturated to nit range [-4, +4] per dimension.
 * 
 * @param w Wave to scale
 * @param factor Scaling factor (nit: -4 to +4)
 * @return Scaled wave
 */
pub func:wave_scale = Wave9(Wave9:w, nit:factor) {
    pass(Wave9 {
        r: w.r * factor,
        s: w.s * factor,
        t: w.t * factor,
        u: w.u * factor,
        v: w.v * factor,
        w: w.w * factor,
        x: w.x * factor,
        y: w.y * factor,
        z: w.z * factor
    });
};

/**
 * Wave Magnitude Squared: Compute |w|² in 9D space
 * 
 * Returns the squared L2 norm of the wave vector. This represents the
 * total energy/probability density of the wave state.
 * 
 * Formula: |w|² = r² + s² + t² + u² + v² + w² + x² + y² + z²
 * 
 * Range: [0, 9*16] = [0, 144] since each nit² ∈ [0, 16]
 * 
 * Note: Explicit conversions required (nit*nit doesn't auto-promote to int32)
 * Each component is manually converted to int32 before multiplication.
 * 
 * @param w Wave to measure
 * @return Squared magnitude (int32)
 */
pub func:wave_magnitude_squared = int32(Wave9:w) {
    // Manual conversion: convert nit to int32 first, then multiply
    // This is verbose but explicit per Aria's design philosophy
    int32:r_val = @cast<int32>(w.r);
    int32:s_val = @cast<int32>(w.s);
    int32:t_val = @cast<int32>(w.t);
    int32:u_val = @cast<int32>(w.u);
    int32:v_val = @cast<int32>(w.v);
    int32:w_val = @cast<int32>(w.w);
    int32:x_val = @cast<int32>(w.x);
    int32:y_val = @cast<int32>(w.y);
    int32:z_val = @cast<int32>(w.z);
    
    int32:r2 = r_val * r_val;
    int32:s2 = s_val * s_val;
    int32:t2 = t_val * t_val;
    int32:u2 = u_val * u_val;
    int32:v2 = v_val * v_val;
    int32:w2 = w_val * w_val;
    int32:x2 = x_val * x_val;
    int32:y2 = y_val * y_val;
    int32:z2 = z_val * z_val;
    
    pass(r2 + s2 + t2 + u2 + v2 + w2 + x2 + y2 + z2);
};

/**
 * Wave Equality: Test if two waves are identical
 * 
 * @param a First wave
 * @param b Second wave
 * @return true if all components match, false otherwise
 */
pub func:wave_equals = bool(Wave9:a, Wave9:b) {
    pass(
        (a.r == b.r) &&
        (a.s == b.s) &&
        (a.t == b.t) &&
        (a.u == b.u) &&
        (a.v == b.v) &&
        (a.w == b.w) &&
        (a.x == b.x) &&
        (a.y == b.y) &&
        (a.z == b.z)
    );
};

/**
 * Compress Wave9 to nyte (9D → 5D Encoding)
 * 
 * Compresses a 9-dimensional wave state into a 5-nit nyte value for
 * compact storage and transmission. This is a lossy projection that
 * preserves the most significant dimensional information.
 * 
 * Encoding Strategy (V1 - Principal Component Projection):
 *   The 9 dimensions are not equally important for all operations.
 *   We prioritize spatial and quantum dimensions over state/time.
 * 
 *   Priority order: x, y, z (spatial) > u, v (quantum) > r, s (state) > t, w (discarded)
 * 
 *   Encoding:
 *     nit0 = x  (spatial X - highest priority for world model)
 *     nit1 = y  (spatial Y)
 *     nit2 = z  (spatial Z)
 *     nit3 = u  (quantum U - primary superposition axis)
 *     nit4 = (r + s + t + v + w) / 5  (averaged minor dimensions)
 * 
 * Future Optimization:
 *   Could use learned PCA projection from actual Nikola wave distributions.
 *   Could implement multiple encoding schemes (spatial-focused, quantum-focused, etc.)
 * 
 * @param w Wave to compress
 * @return Compressed nyte encoding
 */
pub func:nyte_from_wave = nyte(Wave9:w) {
